<p><strong>A. FELONY MURDER example:</strong></p>
<p>Here there was an <strong>unlawful homicide</strong> because KilledPerson was a human being and he was killed by Killer, another human being without legal justification. And it was caused by commission of an<strong> inherently dangerous felony ROBBERY</strong> (or put name of crime), a larceny from the person by force or fear. Killer was taking personal property of another with intent to <strong>permanently deprive</strong> because she was taking &quot;dynamite&quot; (put name of thing which she was stealing) from Killedperson, and she was using force or fear to <strong>overcome his will to resist</strong> because she used a &quot;gun&quot;. The death of Killedperson occured within the <strong>RES GESTAE</strong> of the robbery because he was shot before she left the scene of the crime.</p>
<p>Therefore Killer can be charged with murder for killing Killedperson during the robbery. This would be FIRST DEGREE MURDER because robbery is typically one of the &quot;eneumerated felonies&quot; for the first degree murder.</p>
<p><strong>B. GREAT BODILY INJURY (+others combined)</strong></p>
<p>Here there was an <strong>unlawful homicide</strong> because KilledPerson was a human being and he was killed by Killer, another human being without legal justification. </p>
<p>Here Killer appears to have acted with an <strong>express intent to kill</strong> because she shot KilledPerson in the &quot;head&quot; with a &quot;gun&quot;. These facts imply an intent to kill. Alternatively, Killer clearly intended <strong>great bodily injury</strong> because the homicide was caused by a &quot;firearm&quot;. Use of a firearm implies intent to cause serious bodily harm, regardless of where the victim is shot.</p>
<p>Killer also appears to have acted with an <strong>awareness</strong> and <strong>conscious disregard for danger to human life</strong> because she deliberately shot Killedperson in the head for little good reason. Her act created extreme risks to Ruby, she apparently had an awareness of the risks and consiously disregarded them.</p>
<p>Based on above theories, Killer could be charged with the murder of Killedperson.</p>
<p>It appears Killer killed killedperson willfully and deliberately. If that is proven the murder was FIRST DEGREE. Killer might argue that she did not act willfully and deliberately to kill killedperson and only reacted instinctively because she had a &quot;short fuse&quot;, a MITIGATING FACTOR that caused her to suffer from imparied capacity.</p>
<p>If killer can convince the jury she acted instinctively and did not act willfully, deliberately and with premeditation the murder might be reduced to SECOND DEGREE.</p>
<p><strong>C. FIRST DEGREE MURDER EXAMPLES</strong></p>
<p>Here killer had an <strong>express intent to kill</strong> because she &quot;decided to kill killedperson&quot;. Further, this killing was <strong>willful, deliberate and premediated</strong> because it was planned in advance. Further, this killing was done by <strong>bombing the killedperson</strong> because killer bought dynamite from store and detonate the dynamite under the car of the killed person.</p>
<p>So killer can be charged with FIRST DEGREE MURDER.</p>
<p><strong>D. DEPRAVED HEART THEORY example</strong></p>
<p>Here there was <strong>homicide</strong> because Killedperson was a human being killed by Killer, another human being. Killer may have an <strong>express intent to kill</strong> because she &quot;knew the blast would probably kill killedperson&quot;. But killer would argue that she did not want to kill killedperson because &quot;she felt bad about it.&quot; Regardless, killer deliberately <strong>created extreme risks to human life </strong>with <strong>awareness</strong> of and <strong>conscious disregard</strong> because she &quot;knew the blast would probably kill Killedperson&quot;</p>
<p>Therefore, Killer could be charged with murder based on Depraved Heart Theory of malice.</p>
<p>Further, this would generally be <strong>FIRST DEGREE</strong> murder because the use of explosives to murder is generally one of the &quot;enumerated means&quot; for first degree murder.</p>
<p>Therefore, killer can probably be charged with FIRST DEGREE murder of killedperson even if she did not willfully and deliberately cause his deth with premeditation. She has no defenses.</p>
